article.headline: UCLA 80, Washington 75
article.story: LOS ANGELES (AP) -- UCLA's lineup is going to look different now that the Bruins finally won a game. T.J. Cummings had 18 points and 11 rebounds and UCLA ended its six-game losing streak with a 80-75 victory over Washington on Saturday night. "It feels good," he said. "I'm just glad we got to the other side of that. I'm glad we're back to smiling and having fun." The Bruins won with the help of 25 points from their reserves whose defense proved solid enough to allow the starters more rest. Coach Ben Howland's rotation is usually seven- or eight-deep, but he now plans to use all 10 players. "We're going to follow this formula the rest of the way," he said. "I'm playing guys too many minutes. They are more productive in that amount of time than if they played 37 minutes. To me, it's having the confidence in my bench." Cummings played 32 minutes before fouling out; guards Cedric Bozeman and Dijon Thompson played 28 minutes each; center Ryan Hollins saw 23 minutes of action; and Trevor Ariza played 24 minutes. UCLA also controlled the boards, 40-30, for the first time since beating Arizona State nearly a month ago. The Bruins are 9-1 when they outrebound opponents. The Huskies (10-9, 5-6 Pac-10) had their longest winning streak since 1999 snapped at five games. They've lost 18 straight at Pauley Pavilion, where they last won in 1987. Washington made a late run after being down 11 points with 2:52 remaining. UCLA's Cedric Bozeman turned the ball over on a baseline pass, then Trevor Ariza fouled Brandon Roy with 38 seconds left. Roy made both free throws to get the Huskies to 76-75. Washington used a full-court press, but the Bruins got the ball down the floor and Dijon Thompson was fouled with 30 seconds left. He made both for a 78-75 lead. After a timeout, Mike Jensen's 3-point attempt turned into an airball with 18 seconds left and the Huskies fouled Bozeman. He hit both and the Bruins led 80-75. Nate Robinson's 3-pointer hit only air as time expired. "It got a little scary there at the end. We turned the ball over too many times," Howland said. "These guys are as tired as I am of losing. We beat a team that is the hottest in our league other than Stanford." Roy scored a career-high 30 points for the Huskies, who are coached by former UCLA assistant Lorenzo Romar. "I would've loved to get a win and score only 15 or 20 points," Roy said. "We were 5-0 and got complacent against a team that lost six and wanted it more." Roy was the Huskies' only double-figure scorer. Nate Robinson was held to nine points with UCLA reserve Jon Crispin guarding him. "We didn't play with the energy and fire we have had in the past three weeks and that cost us," Romar said. "Their length and height bothered us and so far this year we haven't matched up well against them." Ariza added 12 points, Thompson had 11 points and backup center Michael Fey scored 10 points -- his first double-figure game in nearly a month. "I told Mike Fey after the game, `Let's pretend every team in our league is Washington," Howland said, noting that Fey's last game in double figures came against Washington on Jan. 10. UCLA (10-9, 6-5) got an important boost from reserves Ryan Walcott and Janou Rubin during a 10-0 run that briefly broke the game open in the second half. Walcott finished with eight points and Rubin added seven. "Coach told us we were going to get more minutes for energy, so we were prepared for it," Walcott said. The Huskies scored eight straight points to tie the game at 38 early in the second half. The teams traded baskets over the next three minutes, with Washington's Tre Simmons hitting a basket that tied it for the last time at 47 with 12:24 remaining. In the Bruins' 10-0 run, Ariza, Rubin and Walcott combined for all the points that gave UCLA a 57-47 lead. The Huskies closed within six points on a 3-pointer by Will Conroy with 4:24 remaining. UCLA pushed its lead back to 11 points with a 5-0 spurt before the Huskies made their comeback. The Bruins led by 11 points in the first half when they shot 47 percent and committed just six turnovers.
